{"text": "the action of symmetries in a layer-polarized basis constrains the structure of the form factors.\n\nThe most significant constraint comes from the anti-unitary spacetime inversion symmetry I. For the following\n\nanalysis, it will be sufficient to work in the particular layer-polarized basis in which its action is as simple as possible.\n\nThis is achieved by mapping the hybrid Wannier layer-polarized basis of Sec. B 3 to \u03c6\u2020(k) \u2192\u03c6\u2020(k)ei\u03b3(k)/2, so that\n\nEq. (B26) becomes\n\n\u02c6I \u02c6\u03c6\u2020(k)\u02c6I\u22121 = \u02c6\u03c6\u2020(k)sxlx.\n\n(C30)\n\nCorrespondingly, Eq. (B21) becomes v\u2020(k)lxv\u2217(k) = \u03c3x, which forgoes the exponential localization of the associated\n\nWannier functions (or equivalently, smoothness of the gauge) while preserving the essential property of maximal layer\n\npolarization. This forces the form factor to obey the following simple constraint:\n\n\u039bq(k) = lx\u039b\u2217\n\nq(k)lx.\n\n(C31)\n\nExpanding the form factor as a linear combination of Pauli matrices \u039bq(k) = P\n\n\u03bc=0,x,y,z \u039b\u03bc\n\nq(k)l\u03bc, then the above\n\nequation is equivalent to\n\n\u039b0\n\nq(k) = \u039b0\n\nq(k)\u2217,\n\n\u039bx\n\nq(k) = \u039bx\n\nq(k)\u2217,\n\n\u039by\n\nq(k) = \u039by\n\nq(k)\u2217,\n\n\u039bz\n\nq(k) = \u2212\u039bz\n\nq(k)\u2217.\n\n(C32)\n\nThe form factor may therefore be written as the following sum of diagonal and off-diagonal terms, with\n\nF S/A\n\nq\n\n(k), \u03a6S/A\n\nq\n\n(k) \u2208R :\n\n\u039bq(k) = F S\n\nq (k)ei\u03a6S\n\nq(k)lz + F A\n\nq (k)lxei\u03a6A\n\nq (k)lz = \u039bS\n\nq(k) + \u039bA\n\nq (k),\n\n(C33)\n\n42\n\nwhich commute and anti-commute with lz, respectively. This expression for the form factor may be verified, by\n\nexplicit calculation, to satisfy the constraint Eq. (C31) above:\n\nlx\u039b\u2217\n\nq(k)lx = F S\n\nq (k)lxe\u2212i\u03a6S\n\nq(k)lzlx + F A\n\nq (k)lxlxe\u2212i\u03a6A\n\nq (k)lzlx = \u039bq(k).\n\n(C34)\n\nTaking the lim